The paper discusses the use of statistical methods to estimate Extrinsic Information Transfer (EXIT) functions, which are commonly used in information theory and communication systems. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of mixed information as an approximation for the true EXIT function, which could fall under the Networked and Distributed Systems (cs.NI) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of a rank-only message passing decoder, which could fall under the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the optimization of post-processing for non-binary Low-Density Parity-Check (LDPC) decoders, which could fall under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
